<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,260,285]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[344,440,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 133–143" captionStartId="115.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@115.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="115" captionText="FIGURES 133–143. leaf mines; 133: Liriomyza arctii Spencer in Ƒerbesina alternifolia; 134: L. asclepiadis Spencer in Asclepias exaltata; 135: L. baccharidis Spencer in Erigeron annuus, lower surface (left) and upper surface (right); 136: L. blechi Spencer in Plantago virginica; 137: L. brassicae (Riley) in Lepidium virginicum; 138: L. eupatoriella Spencer in Ageratina altissima; 139: L. eupatoriella in Ƒernonia baldwinii; 140: L. eupatorii (Kaltenbach) in Baccharis halimifolia; 141: L. fricki Spencer in Trifolium repens; 142: L. galiivora (Spencer) in Galium circaezans (transmitted light); 143: L. ivorcutleri spec. nov. in Silphium perfoliatum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452947/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 136</figureCitation>
) According to 
<bibRefCitation box="[613,939,260,285]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" refId="ref103475" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Stegmaier, C. E. Jr. (1973) Agromyzidae of Florida with a supplement on species from the Caribbean. Arthropods of Florida and Neighboring Land Areas, 7, 1 - 205." type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Stegmaier (1973)</bibRefCitation>
, a number of larvae fed together on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Acanthaceae" genus="Ruellia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="blechum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Ruellia blechum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, “forming a mine primarily along the mid rib with irregular extensions into the leaf blade.” 
<bibRefCitation pageId="47" pageNumber="48" refId="ref103519" refString="Spencer, K. A. &amp; Steyskal, G. C. (1986) Manual of the Agromyzidae (Diptera) of the United States. USDA Agricultural Research Service Agriculture Handbook, 638, 1 - 478. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 119606" type="journal article">Spencer &amp; Steyskal (1986)</bibRefCitation>
described the mine on the same host as “an irregular blotch, normally but not exclusively associated with the midrib or one of the lateral veins.” The mines we found on 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1268,367,392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Plantago" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="virginica">
<emphasis box="[1057,1268,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Plantago virginica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were irregular whitish blotches. One leaf contained a single mine with two larvae, possibly originating in separate mines. Another leaf had three separate mines. Three of these four mines crossed the midrib, but none of them followed it or otherwise reacted to it in any perceptible way. The frass was in discrete black grains and occasional small lumps.
</paragraph>
